{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "In this chapter, I argue that Masham’s work appeals to three common tolerationist principles of her time: the idea that the authorities should not use coercion and penalties as ways of imposing religious beliefs on others; the view that God requires human beings to attain salvation through their own efforts, and not by blindly following the dictates of the state-established religion; and the idea that the granting of liberty of conscience helps to ensure the peace and stability of political society.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "I show that Masham goes further than her tolerationist contemporaries by arguing that together these principles imply that a woman’s intellectual education—or the conscious cultivation of a woman’s ability to reflect critically on her religious beliefs—is vital for the good of the commonwealth.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "Today Masham is not typically thought of as a political writer, even though she makes explicit political comments in both her letters and her final treatise, the Occasional Thoughts.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "So far, no one has interpreted Masham’s final book in light of its engagement with the topical political themes of toleration and liberty of conscience.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "Masham expresses a commitment to three common tolerationist principles of her time: the view that authorities should not use coercion and penalties as ways of imposing religious beliefs on others; the idea that God requires human beings to attain salvation through their own efforts, and not by blindly following the dictates of the state-established religion; and the view that the granting of liberty of conscience helps to ensure the peace and stability of society.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "Masham argues that together these principles imply that a woman’s intellectual education—or the conscious cultivation of a woman’s ability to reflect critically on her religious beliefs—is vital to the flourishing of the commonwealth.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "Masham suggests that the Glorious Revolution—or the ‘Happy Revolution,’ as she calls it elsewhere—brought about positive political changes resulting in the security of ‘Civil and Religious Liberties.’",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "True virtue, in her view, requires conditions of religious and civil liberty in order to flourish—conditions that the 1688-89 revolution helped to secure.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "Masham intends for her book to provide a practical solution to this problem of the cultivation of virtue and true religion within society.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "She proposes a way in which rational creatures might habituate themselves to ‘examine their own Actions by the true Rules and Measures of their Duty.’",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "Masham’s principal solution concerns the proper education of members of society, and the bulk of her book is an account of the principles upon which such an education must be based.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "The first principle of a good education is that every individual must be permitted the liberty to examine and to question their moral and religious beliefs for themselves.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "Masham opposes the use of punishment for religious doubts.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "She highlights the tale of ‘a good Lady of the Church of Rome’ who instructs her child in the doctrine of transubstantiation.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "Masham observes that ‘instead of having their reasonable Inquiries satisfy’d, and incourag’d, Children are ordinarily rebuk’d for making any.’",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "Masham’s principal reasons for opposing punishment and cruelties for religious doubts diverge from those of Locke.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "She does not make the epistemological point that religious belief is involuntary, or that the magistrate does not have certain knowledge of the one true religion, but rather highlights the negative social and spiritual consequences of expecting children to believe without knowing why.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "Masham proposes that women be given a rational education such that they might be able to make a positive contribution to the moral and political well-being of future generations.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU19": {
      "text": "She points out that, among her contemporaries, even the most solicitous about education have ‘employ’d their care herein but by halves,’ because ‘the information and improvement of the Understanding by useful Knowledge (a thing highly necessary to the right regulation of the Manners) is commonly very little thought of in reference to one whole Sex.’",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU20": {
      "text": "Yet a woman’s education is important for the sake of her own spiritual welfare, as well as the welfare of the nation.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
